            <h1 class="margin text-center">sep10 freedom project</h1>
            <h2>Context</h2>
            <p> A project I did in my SEP class was create a webpage based on a movie me and my partner made up. We created a fictional story called "The Adventures of Curious Cat" which is about the advenures that a cat goes on. The point in creating this was to apply all my knowledge on HTML and CSS over the course of about 2 weeks and display it into this webpage. These 2 weeks consisted of writing the story, finding images for it, and tryin to find different ways to make our project pop. We did this using a variety of different colors, fonts, images, and styles. The requirements of the project were to use headings, paragraphs, divs, spans, input fields, google fonts, and CSS selectors. We also had to include images, create a plan using markdown, and specify what parts of the project were done by each partner./p>
            <p>More text about the project.</p>
            <h2>Content</h2>
            <p>During the past couple of weeks in SEP, I´ve been doing a lot of work to teach people about my topic, the Justice System. This included muich research about current technologies, creating potentioal future technologies, and making a responsive website that people can use to obtain all this information. At the end of the year, I presented both my SEP 10 Freedom Project Website and my learning process through my slideshow presentation, The Justice System to my classmates and teachers. To start building my website, I first thought about how I wanted the information to be organized. Since my topic was the justice system, I wanted visitors to easily understand the different parts of the system and how it works. I created different sections for my research and future technology ideas while making sure the website was responsive on different screen sizes. In order to create a 3D model of my future tool, I chose to use A-Frame, a web framework that allows users to create 3D model using HTML. At first, I had very little experience with creating 3D objects on a webpage. I spent time experimenting with different shapes, and positions to understand how A-Frame worked. I eventually created 3D elements that connected to my topic and helped make my website engaging. I also spent time working on the design of my website. I used CSS to improve the appearance of the page and make the information easier to read. I adjusted colors, spacing, and layouts multiple times throughout the project to make everything look cleaner and more organized.
            </p>
            <h1> Reflection:</h1>
            <h2>Challenges</h2>
            <p>During this project, I faced many challenged. One of them was using google fonts, especially using multiple ones. It was hard to organize in the CSS of the project, but I eventually figured it out after going back to previous lessons regarding fonts. Another challenge me and my partners had was communicating with each other. Within the three of us, whetether it was debating about colors, or making up another persons work if absent, it was hard to make it clear what each of us were doing. When al of us were together, we were then able to clear up who should do what task.</p>
            <h2>Takeaways</h2>
            <p>One challenge I faced was learning A-Frame. Since it was a completely new technology for me, I often had to search for tutorials, examples, and documentation to figure out how different features worked. Sometimes my models would not appear correctly, or the camera settings would make it difficult to view them. Through trial and error, I learned how to fix these problems and gained a better understanding of 3D web development. Another challenge was making sure my website contained enough information while still being visually appealing. I spent time balancing content and design so that users could learn about the justice system without being overwhelmed by large amounts of text. I was happy with some parts of my presentation, especially my energy and confidence while speaking. My hook was strong and I had good presence during the presentation. Even though I was nervous, I tried to speak clearly and stay engaged with the audience. However, I also learned that there are areas I can improve in future presentations. One piece of feedback was that I relied too much on reading directly from my slides. Because of this, I was not able to make as much eye contact as I could have.</p>
            <h2>Next Steps</h2>
            <p> For my next steps, I would like to keep improving my website by adding more features and making it easier to use. I want to learn more about web design and coding so I can create better and more interactive websites in the future. This project helped me build important skills, and I plan to continue practicing and challenging myself with new projects to become a more confident and experienced developer.</p>
